I have a SurfaceView class which also implements Runnable, my idea was:

The Main-Thread pushes UI-changes to the SurfaceView. The SurfaceView stores these `UI-Change-Objects` in an `ArrayBlockingQueue`.
This BlockingQueue is then accessed by the SurfaceViews own `Runnable`, like this:

class Screen : SurfaceView, SurfaceHolder.Callback, Runnable {

    private var isRunning = false
    private var updateQueue = ArrayBlockingQueue&lt;Task&gt;(128)
    private lateinit var surfaceHolder : SurfaceHolder

    constructor(context: Context, attr: AttributeSet) : super(context, attr) {
        holder.addCallback(this)
    }

    fun pushChanges(t: Task) {
        updateQueue.add(t)
        if(!isRunning) {
            Thread(this).start()
        }
    }

    override fun run() {
        isRunning = true
        while(updateQueue.isNotEmpty()) {
            val t = updateQueue.remove()

            val ctx = surfaceHolder.lockCanvas()
            /* Rendering with Task t */
            surfaceHolder.unlockCanvasAndPost(ctx)
        }

        isRunning = false
    }
}

`activity_main.xml` has an instance of `Screen` called `renderScreen`. `MainActivity` now pushes changes to `renderScreen` like this:

    renderScreen.pushChanges(task)

Would you consider this a good idea or are there better / more performant ways?

